{"key":"%xCIPjMUteLMo8ygSunJbDPkNdTSwDN376UiAv5tCcRw=.sha256","value":{"previous":"%FwVAVh+HXclDFyMPJ9ZifPx0za/3yoqVq4DNEDQfnIA=.sha256","author":"@/02iw6SFEPIHl8nMkYSwcCgRWxiG6VP547Wcp1NW8Bo=.ed25519","sequence":4507,"timestamp":1462421321024,"hash":"sha256","content":{"type":"post","text":"![value1.png](&ljgHLHd1FDQT8m/7o3KIRz+joBPLEobE8QdOFGh0yUE=.sha256)\n\nnot quite sure what help \"type a\" is here but random processes are fine and all. going to read `PR` as \"random process\" from here forward\n\n![value2.png](&9SOQ9THXFJiNyhgthUg8GzJ71CB3zTTzVl8WnlaM1RY=.sha256)\n\nsome stuff that is discussed in an itemised way. the main thing to start with is that `E_k[[c]]` is the cost evaluator in some currency `k` at the present time, which acts on contract `c`. probably intended oblique reference to \"expected value\" which is often also a big E on a random process at a certain time, and is a nice way to say \"average over a distribution computed for a random variable\", each element of a random process being a random variable of its own.\n\nhonestly the only weird parts are `exch`, `disc`, and `snell`. the other ops are just vector and scalar ops on the random process interpreted as a vector, like slice, add, etc.\n\n![value4.png](&QjGqk4GHU4ldgg1s/uO0P8JtX8vdGTtQmmZCw2PHI40=.sha256)\n\nthe superscript Ts are kinda distracting since they commonly represent \"transpose\" of vectors which are def happening here. anyway...\n\n- disc: converts a random process for which the evaluated values of the contract up to its horizon (so basically, smush distributions and other uncertainties down to numbers) are computed into stochastic currency vals at each of those times up to the horizon. so, smush to expected/evaluated vals, and then fuzzify back into a currency random process!\n\n- exch: just compose one currency val into another. this gets fuzzier if you do it with a floaty exchange rate; computing a function of a random variable (which each of the elements of a random process are) is a convolution of their distributions. if not and you use some evaluated/expected val, you can just multiply by a factor. anyway, it's a vector opt on distributions, like disc.\n\n- snell: i confess that i've not done anything with martingales, but reading https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martingale_(probability_theory)#Submartingales.2C_supermartingales.2C_and_relationship_to_harmonic_functions tells me that the snell envelope is essentially a pessimistic bounding function on random processes. quoth:\n\n> - Consider again the gambler who wins $1 when a coin comes up heads and loses $1 when the coin comes up tails. Suppose now that the coin may be biased, so that it comes up heads with probability p.\n>    - If p is equal to 1/2, the gambler on average neither wins nor loses money, and the gambler's fortune over time is a martingale.\n>    - If p is less than 1/2, the gambler loses money on average, and the gambler's fortune over time is a supermartingale.\n\nsince https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snell_envelope says that a snell envelope is a supermartingale, that seems right enough\n\n> Just as the primitive exch encapsulates assumptions about future exchange rate evolution, so the primitive disc encapsulates an interest rate evolution (Figure 6).\n\nso, since this is finance, time steps also include interest rate calculations. more distributions!\n\nthere is some linearity/associativity about disc:\n\n![value5.png](&8ipCeVWo5zUrtRps6YSVmWIriq9fs688zBtLeHUi+aM=.sha256)\n\nsome talk about intution failing for random vars/processes, cool...\n\na good section talking about computing values basically using finite impulse response (FIR) filters to model interest rates and compute them lazily, instead of trying to grab distributions of interest rates in the future or w/e (and anyway govts set those and are shady outfits anyway)...\n\n> The remaining high-level question is: in the (big) set of possible interest rate models, what is a \"good\" model? The answer is rather incestuous. A candidate interest rate model should price correctly those contracts that are widely traded: one can simply look up the current market prices for them, and compare them with the calculated results. So we look for and later adjust the interest rate model until it \ffits the market data for these simple contracts. Now we are ready to use the model to compute prices for more exotic contracts. The entire market is a gigantic feedback system, and active research studies the problem of its stability.\n\nkinda phones it in tho huh\n\na closing thing:\n\n> We have presented our design as a combinator library embedded in Haskell, and indeed Haskell has proved an excellent host language for prototyping both the library design and various implementation choices. However, our design is absolutely not Haskell-specific\f. The big payout\u000b comes from a declarative approach to describing contracts. As it happens we also used a functional language for implementing the contract language, but that is somewhat incidental.\n\n:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\","root":"%9NYn+97xLhIqI0oPdiWxOckPODa9X267553iFtEDH74=.sha256","branch":"%FwVAVh+HXclDFyMPJ9ZifPx0za/3yoqVq4DNEDQfnIA=.sha256","mentions":[{"link":"&ljgHLHd1FDQT8m/7o3KIRz+joBPLEobE8QdOFGh0yUE=.sha256","name":"value1.png","size":15245,"type":"image/png"},{"link":"&9SOQ9THXFJiNyhgthUg8GzJ71CB3zTTzVl8WnlaM1RY=.sha256","name":"value2.png","size":53984,"type":"image/png"},{"link":"&QjGqk4GHU4ldgg1s/uO0P8JtX8vdGTtQmmZCw2PHI40=.sha256","name":"value4.png","size":35083,"type":"image/png"},{"link":"&8ipCeVWo5zUrtRps6YSVmWIriq9fs688zBtLeHUi+aM=.sha256","name":"value5.png","size":11533,"type":"image/png"}],"channel":"networks"},"signature":"VTj56fna02sL7DXyCSoNZadgBddtAy7n/aCjbwXa41Xt3HHh9F3ECxxpGsMp8BZOwg+HfkzEwzNOqloM94uFBA==.sig.ed25519"},"timestamp":1550671070538}